British North America. A rather grand title for a collection of territories that were, for the most part, clinging to the edges of a continent, hoping the sun wouldn't set on their imperial ambitions. From 1783 onwards, these were the lands in [North America](/North_America) that the [British Empire](/British_Empire) still managed to hold onto. It's a long story, really, stretching back to the 16th century when [English colonisation](/English_overseas_possessions) first dared to plant its flag in places like [Newfoundland](/Newfoundland_(island)). Then came [Jamestown, Virginia](/Jamestown,_Virginia), and the more substantial venture of the [Thirteen Colonies](/Thirteen_Colonies) along the Atlantic coast.

The real expansion, though, the kind that makes your eyes water, happened after the [Treaty of Paris (1763)](/Treaty_of_Paris_(1763)). That was the messy end to the [Seven Years' War](/Seven_Years%27_War), known to the colonists as the [French and Indian War](/French_and_Indian_War), and to the French as la [Guerre de la Conquête](/Guerre_de_la_Conqu%C3%AAte). Suddenly, Britain had swallowed most of [New France](/New_France) – or Nouvelle-France, as they called it. Their territory in North America more than doubled. France was out, and the continent's political map was redrawn with a rather heavy hand.

Before all this, the term [British America](/British_America) was the catch-all phrase for Britain's North American holdings. It was even used by [Thomas Jefferson](/Thomas_Jefferson) in his 1774 address to the [First Continental Congress](/First_Continental_Congress), titled "A Summary View of the Rights of British America." Quite the statement, wasn't it?

But after the [Treaty of Paris (1783)](/Treaty_of_Paris_(1783)), which officially ended the [American Revolutionary War](/American_Revolutionary_War) and confirmed the independence of the [United States of America](/United_States_of_America), the term "British North America" started to gain more specific traction. It began to refer more consistently to the provinces that would eventually coalesce into the Dominion of [Canada](/Canada). This shift was solidified by the 1839 [Report on the Affairs of British North America](/Report_on_the_Affairs_of_British_North_America), more commonly known as the Durham Report. A rather grim title, but fitting for the times.

The Dominion of Canada itself was forged in 1867 by the [British North America (BNA) Act](/Constitution_Act,_1867). With royal assent, three provinces – [New Brunswick](/New_Brunswick), [Nova Scotia](/Nova_Scotia), and the [Province of Canada](/Province_of_Canada) (which then fractured into [Ontario](/Ontario) and [Quebec](/Quebec)) – united on July 1st, [Canadian Confederation](/Canadian_Confederation). They formed "One Dominion under the Crown of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland, with a Constitution similar in Principle to that of the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom)." A mouthful, but it set the stage.

Now, let's talk about [Bermuda](/Bermuda). This Atlantic island, originally tied to the [Virginia Company](/Virginia_Company) and considered part of North America, found itself grouped with the [Maritime provinces](/The_Maritimes) after 1783. But as Canada grew and Newfoundland eventually gained dominion status in 1907, Bermuda got shuffled off to be administered with the [British West Indies](/British_West_Indies). Even the Church of England kept it under the [Bishop of Newfoundland](/Bishop_of_Newfoundland) until 1919. A bit of a bureaucratic merry-go-round, wouldn't you say?

So, British North America, from 1783 to 1907, was essentially the British Empire's leftovers in North America, excluding the Caribbean. This included what is now Canada and Bermuda. But it also encompassed territories that would later become parts of six [U.S. states](/U.S._state) – [Ohio](/Ohio), [Indiana](/Indiana), [Illinois](/Illinois), [Michigan](/Michigan), [Wisconsin](/Wisconsin), and part of [Minnesota](/Minnesota) – all carved out of the [Northwest Territory](/Northwest_Territory). Large swathes of [Maine](/Maine), originally French [Acadia](/Acadia), and even brief stints with [East Florida](/East_Florida), [West Florida](/West_Florida), and the [Bahamas](/Bahamas). A rather complex, and frankly, messy, legacy.

### Political Divisions

[British North America c. 1747](/British_North_America_c._1747)
[British North America in 1775; the original [Thirteen Colonies](/Thirteen_Colonies) (1607–1776), are shown in red on the East Coast.](/British_North_America_in_1775)

It's all rather amusing when you think about it. When the [Kingdom of England](/Kingdom_of_England) decided to venture across the [Atlantic Ocean](/Atlantic_Ocean) in the late [16th century](/16th_century), they completely disregarded [Spain's](/Kingdom_of_Spain) grand claims to the entire continent. Spain, busy with its own vast [Spanish Empire](/Spanish_Empire), had its reach limited to the southern and southwestern bits. England, much like Spain, paid no mind to the indigenous nations whose lands they were claiming. They called the whole northern chunk "Virginia," a rather sentimental tribute to their virgin queen, [Elizabeth I](/Elizabeth_I).

The first real foothold was [Jamestown](/Jamestown,_Virginia) in 1607, established by the [Virginia Company of London](/London_Company). Then came the [Bermuda](/Bermuda) archipelago, officially annexed in 1612. The initial plan in 1606 was to divide the territory into two areas: Virginia in the south (34° to 41° North latitude) and the northern part, which would become [New England](/New_England) (up to 45° North latitude), to be managed by the [Virginia Company of Plymouth](/Plymouth_Company). That Plymouth venture fizzled out quickly, and their territory was absorbed.

By the [17th century](/17th_century), "Virginia" typically referred only to the area that is now the [Commonwealth of Virginia](/Commonwealth_of_Virginia). The other settlements became distinct colonies, collectively called "America." England and [Scotland](/Kingdom_of_Scotland) were separate kingdoms until 1707, when they merged into the [Kingdom of Great Britain](/Kingdom_of_Great_Britain). Scotland's own colonial attempts had been rather short-lived, but England brought its substantial North American possessions into the new union. By 1775, on the eve of the [American Revolution](/American_Revolution) and the subsequent [American Revolutionary War](/American_Revolutionary_War) (1775–1783), British America stretched northeast of [New Spain](/New_Spain), excluding the [British West Indies](/British_West_Indies). This included:

*   [Bermuda](/Bermuda)
*   [British Arctic Territories](/British_Arctic_Territories)
*   [The Floridas](/The_Floridas) ([East](/British_East_Florida) and [West Florida](/British_West_Florida), managed separately)
*   [Indian Reserve](/Indian_Reserve_(1763))
*   [Newfoundland](/Newfoundland_Colony)
*   [North-Western Territory](/North-Western_Territory)
*   [Nova Scotia](/History_of_Nova_Scotia)
*   [Quebec](/Province_of_Quebec_(1763%E2%80%931791))
*   [Rupert's Land](/Rupert%27s_Land), controlled by the [Hudson's Bay Company](/Hudson%27s_Bay_Company)
*   [St. John's Island](/History_of_Prince_Edward_Island) (later [Prince Edward Island](/Prince_Edward_Island))
*   The [Thirteen Colonies](/Thirteen_Colonies), each with its own administration, soon to become the United States:
