#### Bermuda

The Somers Isles, or [Bermuda](/Bermuda), became part of the [Virginia Company's](/Virginia_Company) territory after its flagship, the [Sea Venture](/Sea_Venture), ran aground there in 1609. It was officially added in 1612 and later managed by the [Somers Isles Company](/Somers_Isles_Company) until 1684. Bermuda maintained close ties with Virginia and the [Carolina Colony](/Carolina_Colony). The British Government initially lumped Bermuda in with North America, considering its proximity to the continent – about 640 miles (1,030 km) east-southeast of [Cape Hatteras](/Cape_Hatteras), North Carolina.

[Military Governors and Staff Officers in garrisons of British North America and West Indies 1778 and 1784](/Military_Governors_and_Staff_Officers_in_garrisons_of_British_North_America_and_West_Indies_1778_and_1784)

Despite having familial and trade connections to the southern American colonies, Bermudians initially leaned towards the rebels during the [American Revolutionary War](/American_Revolutionary_War) / [American War of Independence](/American_War_of_Independence). However, the [Royal Navy's](/Royal_Navy) control of the [Atlantic Ocean](/Atlantic_Ocean) made joining the rebellion impossible. While some Bermudians supplied ships and gunpowder to the rebels, Bermudian privateers soon turned their attention to rebel shipping. After the [Treaty of Paris (1783)](/Treaty_of_Paris_(1783)) officially recognized the [United States of America](/United_States_of_America), Bermuda was administratively grouped with the [Maritime](/The_Maritimes) and [Newfoundland and Labrador](/Newfoundland_and_Labrador) provinces of eastern [Canada](/Canada), and more broadly, with British North America.

Following the war, the [Royal Navy](/Royal_Navy) spent years charting Bermuda's reefs to find safe passage into the Great Sound and [Hamilton Harbour](/Hamilton_Harbour,_Bermuda). A naval base was established in 1794, initially in [St. George's](/St._George%27s,_Bermuda), before the construction of the [Royal Naval Dockyard, Bermuda](/Royal_Naval_Dockyard,_Bermuda). The command area shifted over time, but by 1821, Bermuda became the year-round headquarters for the North America and West Indies Station. The [Royal Naval Dockyard, Halifax](/Royal_Naval_Dockyard,_Halifax) was eventually handed over to the [Dominion of Canada](/Canada) in 1907.

Before 1784, the [Bermuda Garrison](/Bermuda_Garrison) fell under the military command in New York. A regular infantry garrison had existed from 1701 to 1768, supplemented by the militia. This garrison was re-established in 1794 with elements of the [47th Regiment of Foot](/47th_Regiment_of_Foot) and the [Royal Artillery](/Royal_Artillery). The Bermuda Garrison remained part of the Nova Scotia Command until 1869. During the [War of 1812](/War_of_1812), British forces based in Bermuda engaged in actions against the United States, including the [Chesapeake Campaign](/Chesapeake_Campaign) of 1813–1814, which saw the [Burning of Washington](/Burning_of_Washington). The garrison was significantly expanded throughout the 19th century to protect the naval base and serve as a launchpad for amphibious operations.

The [Church of England](/Church_of_England) in Bermuda was linked to the [See of Nova Scotia](/Diocese_of_Nova_Scotia_and_Prince_Edward_Island) from 1825 to 1839. From 1839, it became part of the [Diocese of Newfoundland and Bermuda](/Diocese_of_Newfoundland). A separate Bermuda Synod was established in 1879, but it wasn't until 1919 that Bermuda had its own bishop, the [Bishop of Bermuda](/Bishop_of_Bermuda). Later, in 1949, the Diocese of Newfoundland joined the [Anglican Church of Canada](/Anglican_Church_of_Canada). Today, the Anglican Church of Bermuda is one of six [extra-provincial Anglican churches](/Extra-provincial_Anglican_churches) under the [Archbishop of Canterbury](/Archbishop_of_Canterbury).

Roman Catholic worship, outlawed after the [English Reformation](/English_Reformation), was re-established in Bermuda under restrictions that lasted until the [20th century](/20th_century). Bermuda was part of the [Archdiocese of Halifax, Nova Scotia](/Roman_Catholic_Archdiocese_of_Halifax-Yarmouth) until 1953, when it became the [Apostolic Prefecture of Bermuda Islands](/Roman_Catholic_Diocese_of_Hamilton_in_Bermuda). The first [African Methodist Episcopal Church](/African_Methodist_Episcopal_Church) in Bermuda, established in 1885, was previously part of the [British Methodist Episcopal Church](/British_Methodist_Episcopal_Church) of Canada.

### New France (Nouvelle-France)

The [Kingdom of Great Britain](/Kingdom_of_Great_Britain) acquired significant portions of [Acadia or Acadie, Nouvelle-France](/Acadia) after the [Queen Anne's War](/Queen_Anne%27s_War) (1702–1713) and further territories following the [Seven Years' War](/Seven_Years%27_War) / [French and Indian War](/French_and_Indian_War) (1753/1756-1763). These lands would eventually form the provinces of [Nova Scotia](/Nova_Scotia), [New Brunswick](/New_Brunswick), and [Prince Edward Island](/Prince_Edward_Island), as well as parts of [Quebec](/Quebec) in modern [Canada](/Canada). Some territories also became part of the old [Massachusetts Bay Colony](/Massachusetts_Bay_Colony), later the [Commonwealth of Massachusetts](/Massachusetts), and eventually the [State of Maine](/Maine) in 1820.

Britain gained much of the rest of [Canada (New France)](/Canada_(New_France)) and eastern [Louisiana](/Louisiana_(New_France)), including West Florida, from [France](/Kingdom_of_France), and [East Florida](/East_Florida) from [Spain](/Kingdom_of_Spain), through the [Treaty of Paris (1763)](/Treaty_of_Paris_(1763)). Spain had actually ceded its claim to [Spanish Louisiana](/Spanish_Louisiana) to France in 1762 but didn't take possession until 1769. The [Treaty of Paris (1783)](/Treaty_of_Paris_(1783)) saw the United States acquire the southern and western parts of New France, south of the [Great Lakes](/Great_Lakes) and extending to the [Ohio River](/Ohio_River) and [Mississippi River](/Mississippi_River). Spain, meanwhile, regained [East Florida](/East_Florida) and held onto the [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico) coastline of [West Florida](/West_Florida), forming [Spanish Florida](/Spanish_Florida) until its cession to the U.S. in 1813/1819.

[British possessions](/British_possessions) on the North American continent. c. 1830

Nova Scotia was divided into modern-day [Nova Scotia](/Nova_Scotia) and [New Brunswick](/New_Brunswick) in 1784. The remaining part of Quebec was split in 1791 into the French-speaking [Lower Canada](/Lower_Canada) (future [Quebec](/Quebec)) and the English-speaking [Upper Canada](/Upper_Canada) (future [Ontario](/Ontario)). These two provinces were later merged in 1841 into the [Province of Canada](/Province_of_Canada), a union that lasted until 1867 when the [British North America Act](/British_North_America_Act) was passed, leading to the formation of the [Dominion of Canada](/Canada).

After the [War of 1812](/War_of_1812), the [Treaty of 1818](/Treaty_of_1818) established the [49th parallel, north](/49th_parallel_north) of [latitude](/Latitude) as the border between the United States and British North America, stretching from Rupert's Land west to the [Rocky Mountains](/Rocky_Mountains). Twenty-eight years later, in 1846, the [Oregon Treaty](/Oregon_Treaty) split the jointly-administered [Oregon Country](/Oregon_Country) lands in the [Pacific Northwest](/Pacific_Northwest) between the U.S. and Britain, extending the 49th parallel to the [Puget Sound](/Puget_Sound). Britain kept the offshore islands along the [West Coast](/West_Coast_of_North_America), including [Vancouver Island](/Vancouver_Island).

[British possessions in North America, (ca. 1855)](/British_possessions_in_North_America,_ca._1855)

The boundary between [Maine](/Maine) and [Nova Scotia](/Nova_Scotia) was finally settled by the [Webster–Ashburton Treaty](/Webster%E2%80%93Ashburton_Treaty) in 1842.

[The Canadas](/The_Canadas) were unified into the [Province of Canada](/Province_of_Canada) in 1841.

On July 1, 1867, the Dominion of Canada was created by the [British North America Act, 1867](/British_North_America_Act,_1867). This [confederation process](/Confederation_of_Canada) brought together Canada, New Brunswick, and Nova Scotia. The former Province of Canada was re-divided into [Canada East](/Canada_East) (now [Quebec](/Quebec)) and [Canada West](/Canada_West) (now [Ontario](/Ontario)).

Following confederation in 1867, the British Army withdrew from Canada in 1871, handing defense over to the [Canadian Militia](/Canadian_Militia). With the end of the Nova Scotia Command and the office of [Commander-in-Chief for British North America](/Commander-in-Chief,_North_America), the Bermuda Garrison was elevated to a distinct Bermuda Command.

### Newfoundland, Rupert's Land, and other territories of British North America

The [Colony of Newfoundland](/Colony_of_Newfoundland), much like Bermuda, was not part of the 1867 confederation that formed the Dominion of Canada.

In 1870, [Rupert's Land](/Rupert%27s_Land), the vast territory controlled by the [Hudson's Bay Company](/Hudson%27s_Bay_Company), was annexed by Canada and became the [North-West Territories](/Northwest_Territories) (NWT), along with the new province of [Manitoba](/Manitoba). [British Columbia](/British_Columbia), the British colony on the west coast north of the [49th parallel](/49th_parallel_north), including [Vancouver Island](/Vancouver_Island), joined Canada as its sixth province in 1871. Prince Edward Island followed in 1873 as the seventh. The border of British Columbia with [Washington Territory](/Washington_Territory) was settled in 1872, and with [Alaska](/Alaska) in 1903.

The [Arctic Archipelago](/Arctic_Archipelago) was ceded by Britain to Canada in 1880 and incorporated into the North-West Territories. Later, large portions of the NWT were carved out as new territories ([Yukon Territory](/Yukon_Territory) in 1898 and [Nunavut](/Nunavut) in 1999) or became provinces ([Alberta](/Alberta) and [Saskatchewan](/Saskatchewan), both in 1905), or were absorbed by existing provinces ([Manitoba](/Manitoba), [Ontario](/Ontario), and [Quebec](/Quebec)).

Then, in 1907, [Newfoundland](/Newfoundland_Colony) achieved [Dominion of Newfoundland](/Dominion_of_Newfoundland) status. This left Bermuda as the sole remaining colony in British North America. British North America, as an administrative region, ceased to exist. All remaining British colonies in the Western Hemisphere, from Bermuda to the [Falkland Islands](/Falkland_Islands), were grouped under the "West Indian Division" of the "Crown Colonies Department" of the Colonial Office.

In 1934, Newfoundland reverted to British administration under the [Commission of Government](/Newfoundland_Commission_of_Government). Bermuda, meanwhile, was increasingly seen by the British Government as being part of, or at least conveniently grouped with, the British West Indies. The last administrative tie to the Maritimes was through the church. In 1879, the Synod of the Church of England in Bermuda was formed, and the Diocese of Bermuda became separate from the Diocese of Newfoundland. However, they continued to share a bishop until 1919, when each received its own.

In 1949, [Newfoundland](/Newfoundland_(island)) and its mainland territory of [Labrador](/Labrador) joined Canada as its tenth province.

Canada's journey toward semi-independence began in 1867, and full sovereignty over foreign affairs was achieved with the [Statute of Westminster 1931](/Statute_of_Westminster_1931). Canada gained the right to establish and accept foreign embassies, starting with Washington, D.C. The final vestiges of constitutional dependence on Britain were removed when Canadians agreed on a method for amending their constitution. This was implemented by the British Parliament passing the [Canada Act 1982](/Canada_Act_1982) at the request of the [Senate](/Senate_of_Canada) and [House of Commons of Canada](/House_of_Commons_of_Canada), with the support of nine of the ten [provinces of Canada](/Provinces_and_territories_of_Canada).

### British North America Colonies

After the 1776 declaration of independence by the colonies that formed the United States (recognized by Britain in 1783), the remaining territories were administered by the [Home Office](/Home_Office), which controlled military affairs until 1794 when that responsibility transferred to the [War Office](/War_Office). The Home Office managed the remaining North American continental colonies and Bermuda, referring to them collectively as British North America. In 1801, administration shifted to the War Office, which became the War and Colonial Office. The [Secretary of State for War](/Secretary_of_State_for_War) also became the [Secretary of State for War and the Colonies](/Secretary_of_State_for_War_and_the_Colonies) until 1854, when the War and Colonial Office split into the [War Office](/War_Office) and the [Colonial Office](/Colonial_Office).

Prior to the 1846 [Oregon Treaty](/Oregon_Treaty), the continental colonies included:

*   [Province of Canada](/Province_of_Canada) (previously [Upper Canada](/Upper_Canada) and [Lower Canada](/Lower_Canada))
*   [Newfoundland](/Colony_of_Newfoundland)
*   [Nova Scotia](/Nova_Scotia)
*   [New Brunswick](/New_Brunswick)
*   [Prince Edward Island](/Prince_Edward_Island)
*   [Rupert's Land](/Rupert%27s_Land)
*   [British Arctic Territories](/British_Arctic_Territories)
*   [Columbia District](/Columbia_District)/[Oregon Country](/Oregon_Country) (shared with the United States) [1] [21]

Bermuda, the oceanic archipelago, while not strictly part of the Americas, was included due to its proximity to Nova Scotia.

### Administration

Beyond the individual colonial governments, British North America was directly administered from London.

Except for territories managed by the [Honourable East India Company](/Honourable_East_India_Company) and protectorates, the British Empire (excluding Rupert's Land) was overseen by the [Board of Trade](/Board_of_Trade) until 1783. From 1783 to 1801, it was the [Home Office](/Home_Office). Then, from 1801 to 1854, it was the [War Office](/War_Office) (later the War and Colonial Office), with the Secretary of State for War also handling colonial affairs. From 1824, the [British Empire](/British_Empire) was divided into four administrative departments by the War and Colonial Office: NORTH AMERICA, WEST INDIES, MEDITERRANEAN AND AFRICA, and EASTERN COLONIES. The North America department included: [23]

**North America**

*   [Upper Canada](/Upper_Canada), [Lower Canada](/Lower_Canada)
*   [New Brunswick](/New_Brunswick), [Nova Scotia](/Nova_Scotia), [Prince Edward Island](/Prince_Edward_Island)
*   [Bermuda](/Bermuda), [Newfoundland](/Newfoundland)

Until 1846, the postal system operated with a deputy in British North America, overseen from London. [24]

The [Colonial Office](/Colonial_Office) and War Office, along with their respective Secretaries of State, were separated in 1854. [1] [21] From that point until the [confederation](/Canadian_Confederation) of Canada in 1867, the War Office divided military administration of British colonial and foreign stations into nine districts. The "North America And North Atlantic" district included: [25]

**North America and North Atlantic**

*   New Westminster (British Columbia)
*   Newfoundland
*   Quebec
*   Halifax
*   Kingston, Canada West
*   Bermuda

By 1862, the Colonial Office oversaw eight colonies in British North America: [26]

**North American Colonies, 1862**

*   Canada
*   Nova Scotia
*   New Brunswick
*   Prince Edward Island
*   Newfoundland
*   Bermuda
*   Vancouver Island
*   British Columbia

By 1867, the administration of the [Falkland Islands](/Falkland_Islands) in the [South Atlantic Ocean](/South_Atlantic_Ocean) had been added to the North American Department of the Colonial Office. [27]

**North American Department of the Colonial Office, 1867**

*   Canada
*   Nova Scotia
*   New Brunswick
*   Prince Edward Island
*   Newfoundland
*   Bermuda
*   Vancouver Island
*   British Columbia
*   Falkland Islands

After the 1867 confederation of most British North American colonies into the Dominion of Canada, Bermuda and Newfoundland remained the only British colonies in North America. The Falkland Islands also continued to be administered by the North American Department. [28] Although the British Government was no longer [responsible](/Responsible_government) for Canada, its relationship with Canada and other dominions remained under the purview of the [Secretary of State for the Colonies](/Secretary_of_State_for_the_Colonies) until the creation of the [Secretary of State for Dominion Affairs](/Secretary_of_State_for_Dominion_Affairs) in 1925. The reduction in territory led to a reorganization of the Colonial Office. In 1901, its departments included: North American and Australasian; West Indian; Eastern; South African; and West African.

The "North American and Australasian Department" included: [29]

**North American and Australasian Department, 1901**

*   Canada
*   Newfoundland
*   Bermuda
*   Bahamas
*   British Honduras
*   New South Wales
*   Victoria
*   South Australia
*   Queensland
*   Western Australia
*   Tasmania, New Zealand
*   Fiji
*   British New Guinea
*   Western Pacific
*   Cyprus
*   Gibraltar
*   Falkland Islands

In 1907, the [Colony of Newfoundland](/Colony_of_Newfoundland) became the [Dominion of Newfoundland](/Dominion_of_Newfoundland), leaving the [Imperial fortress](/Imperial_fortress) of Bermuda as the last remaining British North American colony.

Bermuda, with its small landmass (less than 21 square miles) and population, could hardly stand as an administrative region on its own. By 1908, the Colonial Office had two main departments: one for dominions and protectorates, and another for crown colonies. The Crown Colonies Department was divided into four territorial divisions: Eastern, West Indian, East African and Mediterranean, and West African.

The West Indian Division now encompassed all remaining British colonies in the Western Hemisphere, from Bermuda to the Falkland Islands:

Jamaica, Turks Islands, British Honduras, British Guiana, Bahamas, Bermuda, Trinidad, Barbados, Windward Islands, Leeward Islands, Falkland Islands, and St. Helena. [30]

